  "published": "2021-11-19",
  "runtimeMin": 108,
  "format": "Bill Simmons joins Sean and Amanda on the Will Smith Williams-sisters movie 'King Richard,' then the three of them count down their five favorite sports movies. Plus: director Ronaldo Marcus Green on making it.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'King Richard'",
      "note": "With Bill Simmons",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "King Richard",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "Will Smith as Richard Williams, raising Venus and Serena in 1990s Compton. The group reads it as a parent movie more than a sports movie: Bill's takeaway is how far it shifts his '90s memory of Richard as a lunatic tennis dad, and both he and Amanda flag the kitchen-argument scene (Aunjanue Ellis as Oracene going toe-to-toe) as the thing that lifts it past a generic sports film. Praise for Jon Bernthal and Tony Goldwyn as the coaches, the daughters played by Saniyya Sidney and Demi Singleton, and Robert Elswit's cinematography. Sean's one knock: the final-match sequence runs too long. Pegged as a Will Smith Oscar lock and best-picture contender."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The four eras of the sports movie",
      "note": "Bill Simmons on where the genre has been and where it's going",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Longest Yard",
          "year": 1974,
          "note": "Bill's first era starts here in '74."
        },
        {
          "title": "Rollerball",
          "year": 1975
        },
        {
          "title": "Rocky",
          "year": 1976,
          "note": "With Bad News Bears, the two 1976 films that kick the genre into gear."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Bad News Bears",
          "year": 1976
        },
        {
          "title": "Major League",
          "year": 1989,
          "note": "Bill's second run, late '80s into the '90s kids-and-comedy wave."
        },
        {
          "title": "Jerry Maguire",
          "year": 1996,
          "note": "The '90s move that takes the formula and twists it up a notch."
        },
        {
          "title": "Tin Cup",
          "year": 1996
        },
        {
          "title": "Hardball",
          "year": 2001,
          "note": "Third era: one star on a poster, a movie about whatever, and it makes money."
        },
        {
          "title": "Remember the Titans",
          "year": 2000
        },
        {
          "title": "Varsity Blues",
          "year": 1999
        },
        {
          "title": "Summer Catch",
          "year": 2001
        },
        {
          "title": "Love & Basketball",
          "year": 2000,
          "note": "One of the good ones from the third generation."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Damned United",
          "year": 2009,
          "note": "Part of the current era Bill likes best: real movies that happen to be set in sports rather than the old template."
        },
        {
          "title": "Warrior",
          "year": 2011,
          "note": "A family story that lives inside professional sports; the kind of invented-world film Bill argues you now have to build to get these made."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Way Back",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Makes the playoffs and then keeps going off a cliff into rehab; twists the old formula against you, and Bill thinks it's great."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Sean's Top 5 Sports Movies",
      "note": "favorites, not best; No. 1 first",
      "subject": "sports movies",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Bull Durham",
          "year": 1988,
          "note": "No. 1 - Ron Shelton's minor-league catcher movie; Sean rates Costner as the most credible actor-athlete in movie history and calls it the 'I didn't know you could do that' kind of film."
        },
        {
          "title": "Slapshot",
          "year": 1977,
          "note": "No. 2 - George Roy Hill and Paul Newman; maybe Newman's best performance, no hockey movie has come near it in 45 years."
        },
        {
          "title": "White Men Can't Jump",
          "year": 1992,
          "note": "No. 3 - the other Ron Shelton pick; Woody Harrelson and Wesley Snipes with all-time chemistry, first 45 minutes unassailable."
        },
        {
          "title": "Downhill Racer",
          "year": 1969,
          "note": "No. 4 - Michael Ritchie's cerebral skiing movie with Robert Redford as a prima-donna Olympian; the one that never leaves Sean's list, and Gene Hackman's audition for Hoosiers."
        },
        {
          "title": "Rounders",
          "year": 1998,
          "note": "No. 5 - a poker movie that has every sports-movie beat; Sean's love of it has famously been used against him on the podcast."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Bill Simmons's Top 5 Sports Movies",
      "note": "favorites, not best; No. 1 first",
      "subject": "sports movies",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Caddyshack",
          "year": 1980,
          "note": "No. 1 - pure enjoyment; still one of the funniest movies ever, and Ted Knight steals every scene he's in."
        },
        {
          "title": "Slapshot",
          "year": 1977,
          "note": "No. 2 - Bill had it at two as well; owns its sport, nothing has approached it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hoosiers",
          "year": 1986,
          "note": "No. 3 - used to be his No. 1; Spike Lee's writing on its racial politics complicated it for him, but Jimmy's performance is unbelievable. Doing it on The Rewatchables next week."
        },
        {
          "title": "Rocky III",
          "year": 1982,
          "note": "No. 4 - the most satisfying Rocky start to finish, the best twist, the Mr. T statue scene, the beach jumping."
        },
        {
          "title": "Blue Chips",
          "year": 1994,
          "note": "No. 5 - William Friedkin college-hoops drama with Nick Nolte and Shaq; a flawed movie Bill loves anyway, and revealing now given college-athlete pay debates."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Amanda's Top 5 Sports Movies",
      "note": "favorites, not best; No. 1 first",
      "subject": "sports movies",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Moneyball",
          "year": 2011,
          "note": "No. 1 - the heart pick; a new era of the genre, Brad Pitt's best performance for her, and a climactic home run she finds nearly as moving as the end of Rudy. She only forgot to mention Philip Seymour Hoffman."
        },
        {
          "title": "A League of Their Own",
          "year": 1992,
          "note": "No. 2 - a sisters movie not unlike King Richard; Tom Hanks, Madonna and Rosie O'Donnell, and the did-she-drop-it-on-purpose question (Amanda says yes)."
        },
        {
          "title": "Rudy",
          "year": 1993,
          "note": "No. 3 - grew up in a college-football household; weeps throughout every time, made-up jersey scene and all."
        },
        {
          "title": "Creed",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "No. 4 - a reinvention that keeps the Rocky spirit; the Meek Mill training scene and the steps let her channel her husband's Philadelphia pride."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Cutting Edge",
          "year": 1992,
          "note": "No. 5 - the idiosyncratic Amanda pick; a Tony Gilroy-scripted figure-skating rom-com with DB Sweeney and the training montages her Olympics-obsessed kid self loved."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation",
      "note": "Ronaldo Marcus Green on directing 'King Richard'",
      "guest": "Ronaldo Marcus Green on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "King Richard",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "How he landed the job (script slipped to him by four people, a pitch built on his own athlete father rather than a visual deck), why he wanted a family movie with tennis in it and not a tennis movie, and the liberties he took with the timeline and the smaller real-life final match to make it cinematic. Recruited cinematographer Robert Elswit after meeting him at a Sundance directors' lab, then moved down the street from him."
        },
        {
          "title": "Monsters and Men",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "His first feature, based on his life, and the film that took him to Sundance."
        },
        {
          "title": "Joe Bell",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "The sophomore film with Mark Wahlberg he was finishing when the King Richard call came."
        },
        {
          "title": "Searching for Bobby Fischer",
          "year": 1993,
          "note": "One of the touchstones (with Moneyball) he cited to Will as the tone he was after - a sports movie about a family, not the sport."
        },
        {
          "title": "Nomadland",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "The last great film he'd seen: Chloe Zhao, an NYU friend, making a big-hearted movie with no lights."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
